    <item>
      <title>Physics and Mathematics Instruction</title>
      <link>https://swmusser.github.io/post/physics-instruction/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 20 Apr 2016 00:00:00 -0400</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://swmusser.github.io/post/physics-instruction/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;In many of the physics courses I&amp;rsquo;ve taken in my undergraduate and graduate years &lt;em&gt;The Feynman Lectures on Physics&lt;/em&gt; have been presented as the gold standard when it comes to physics instruction. They certainly left their impact on me; Feynman&amp;rsquo;s discussion of thermodynamics as illustrated by the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brownian_ratchet&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Brownian ratchet&lt;/a&gt; is a fresh way to approach the subject and I find myself returning to it from time to time. As with this example, much of Feyman&amp;rsquo;s technique relied on rebuilding a subject&amp;rsquo;s instruction from the ground up, attempting to present every subject with maximum appeal to intuition. That approach worked well for him in part because he was a genius and in part because he &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Feynman#Pedagogy&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;devoted a lot of time to preparing the lectures&lt;/a&gt;. This makes Feynman&amp;rsquo;s method of instruction nigh on impossible to replicate by your average physicist, though some do try with varying success.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A better model for your average physics instructor is, in my view, &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.damtp.cam.ac.uk/user/tong/teaching.html&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;David Tong&amp;rsquo;s lecture notes&lt;/a&gt;. I think his real success is not necessarily in rebuilding entire subjects, but rather in presenting them in a way that is easily digestible by a motivated student.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
